article.description: Steve Nash scored 28 points and Dirk Nowitzki had 26 points and 21 rebounds, and Dallas got plenty of help from its newcomers, as the Mavericks beat the Sacramento Kings 111-97 Saturday in a battle of division leaders.
article.headline: Nash, Nowitzki get help from newcomers to beat Kings

images.name: Van Exel, Nick 020223 inline
images.caption: Nick Van Exel had eight points and eight assists in his Dallas debut.

article.linkText: Nash, Nowitzki, newcomers send Mavs past Kings
article.story:
DALLAS (AP) -- The newcomers fit in nicely for the Dallas Mavericks. But Steve Nash and Dirk Nowitzki still led the way. Nash scored 28 points and Nowitzki had 26 points and 21 rebounds as the Mavericks, with key contributions from Raef LaFrentz and Nick Van Exel in their debuts, beat the Sacramento Kings 111-97 Saturday in a battle of division leaders. "We looked good and the new guys fit in well," Nowitzki said. "It will be a while before we really know how to play with each other, but the future is bright." LaFrentz had 14 points and six rebounds, while Van Exel had eight points and eight assists. Both played about 30 minutes just two days after coming from Denver with Avery Johnson and Tariq Abdul-Wahad in a deal completed just before the NBA trading deadline. In the end, the Mavericks' two All-Stars still made the difference. Nash shot 10-for-13 in the game and scored 15 straight points in a 22-6 third-quarter run that put Dallas ahead to stay. Nowitzki had his second straight game with more than 20 points and 20 rebounds. "I got a few good looks. I knocked them down and got my confidence going. That made it easy for me," Nash said. "With the new guys, we can really spread the floor and give a lot of different looks." The Kings had a 58-51 lead when Chris Webber made a 19-foot jumper with 9:07 left in the third quarter. Nash then started the turnaround for Dallas, making consecutive 3-pointers to begin his personal scoring run. "He can do that in a heartbeat," Nowitzki said. "He's the heart and soul of the whole team." Nash tied the game at 64 when he hit a short jumper with 4:09 left in the third quarter. After Scot Pollard traveled, Nash drove for a layup that put the Mavericks ahead to stay, and ended his stretch of 15 straight points. Webber had 28 points and 14 rebounds for the Kings. Sacramento, despite losing three of its last four games, still has the NBA's best record (40-15) and a two-game lead over the Los Angeles Lakers in the Pacific Division. Dallas, the Midwest leader, has the league's second-best record at 39-17. "They got to running and took control, and we got impatient," Kings coach Rick Adelman said. "They've got that many more weapons to go with. It was a good trade for them." LaFrentz ended Nash's 15-point spurt with a 3-pointer. The Mavericks had a 77-67 lead by the end of the third quarter, and the Kings never got closer than seven points after that. "It was a very good game and it was a special game that we will all remember," Mavericks coach Don Nelson said. "But we have four new guys and it is going to take a while. I don't want to get too excited." Michael Finley added 14 points for Dallas, while Johnny Newman had 13. Peja Stojakovic, who scored 63 points in the first two games this season against Dallas, had 16 points. Mike Bibby, Doug Christie and Bobby Jackson each scored 13. Nash and Van Exel went on the floor for the first time together when the game was tied with 6:09 left in the second quarter. Van Exel took over the role that Tim Hardaway had before he was sent with Juwan Howard and Donnell Harvey to the Nuggets. Within 2 minutes, the Kings led 43-36 after Stojakovic hit a 3-pointer and Webber had a tip-in and a follow-up slam. But the Mavericks needed just 2 minutes to score eight straight points. Van Exel fed LaFrentz for a 3-pointer, Nash made a 3-pointer and Finley drove for a layup. "I didn't expect to be in a game of this magnitude this year," said Van Exel, who was part of only 16 wins in Denver this season. "I was real nervous and finally glad that I settled into the game." With less than five minutes left, Van Exel was driving for what appeared to be an easy layup. He instead passed to Finley, who was wide open for a 3-pointer that extended the lead to 96-83.

Game notes
Sacramento led 52-48 at halftime. ... The Mavericks went ahead with their planned giveaway of 5,000 Hardaway bobblehead dolls. ... Evan Eschmeyer made his fifth start for Dallas, playing the first 10 minutes before LaFrentz -- who started all 51 games in Denver -- came into the game. Eschmeyer never returned. ... Sacramento lost consecutive games for only the fourth time this season. The last time was Dec. 19-22. ... Johnson scored a bucket while playing the last three minutes, while Abdul-Wahad was scoreless with three fouls in six minutes.
